I love winter and I love #Calgary. Any Calgarians out there? #goflamesgo

I was fortunate enough to grow up with views like this not far from my home. And even spending so much time hiking these peaks, driving these roads, jumping in these lakes, I still crave it all the time. I still get excited smelling that fresh air, seeing the same mountains and feeling the chill of glacial water. Anyone else feel that way?
Beautiful #Dall sheep in #Kluane National Park, #Yukon #Canada.

I watched a video today about a couple who lived off the grid far away from anyone else, hunting and farming their own food, surfing, exploring and waking up every morning to the sea, mountains and untouched wilderness. (Check out the link in my bio to watch the video). My first thought was how I could make that happen someday. Have you ever wanted to do something like that? Do you think you actually could?

When I shot this picture I was on a month long road trip up to #Alaska. I remember being on the road in my old noisy 1986 Toyota Land Cruiser HJ60 and was looking up at the foggy peaks. I had to pull over when I saw this hill with thick fog that was moving like a river through the trees. I'd never seen anything quite like it. Nature never ceases to amaze me.

Feeling grateful for the places, people, and experiences that inspire me. It brings me back to the reasons I stopped pursuing dental school and got into photography in the first place. I had no idea where I was going or how to get there, just an overwhelming passion for creating photos and the support and encouragement of you guys here on @Instagram. Thanks to those who's work I've loved to follow for years, and for those who have appreciated mine. You guys are the best. ‚úåüèº

Before I ever bought my first camera 4 years ago, I loved to travel and hike and camp and experience new places. I never took pictures of places like East Africa, Peru, and the Canadian Arctic. I just didn't care to. Photos aren't life. I still like to put down my camera and soak in real life. I know for many people it's the opposite, but Hawaii is one of those places that make me want to forget the camera. I do still love to get a few shots though to remember it. And to all my friends new and old on Oahu, thanks. You guys are the reason I come back. #hawaii #oahu @harimarishoes #HariMari
A quiet lake in the Canadian Rockies. Not another soul in sight.
The wild is not there for us to conquer. It is enough to be a pebble at the foot of the mountain or a drop in a raging river.
Made a quick trip to #Waterton today. Check out my Instagram story to see more. @watertonlakesnationalpark

On the hike in we came across large cougar tracks along much of the trail. On the way out there were some smaller cougar tracks. They're shy animals with a talent for hiding. As much as it bothers me that I've never seen a cougar in the wild, I suppose it's also a good thing. Have any of you seen one in the wild?
For experiences like this you can't be scared by a little snow and freezing temperatures.

That road life. Sometimes it just feels like late nights and greasy food. Other times you look in your rear view mirror and realize you accidentally found one of the most iconic roads in the United States. #monumentvalley #utah #utahisrad #roadtrip

I always appreciate the support from you guys even when I'm not always great at posting on social media. I've been surprised at how many people notice. Sometimes I'm just busy enjoying real life. The last couple weeks have been a lot of fun though road tripping through the states. I'll try to get some photos up soon.

The edge of shrinking, frozen world: Today many of my friends and colleagues are marching for science. I‚Äôve spent years working on the front lines of climate change seeing rivers dry, glaciers dwindle and our frozen realms shrink.  The science explaining this rapid rate of change is agreed upon by 97% of planets scientific leaders and yes, we are playing a hand in it, all of us, myself included. It shouldn‚Äôt be political though.  It should simply be a call to change, to find solutions and innovations together to protect this beautiful blue sphere we all share. Lurking below: Swimming inside ‚Äúshark city‚Äù made me terrified, but now I am fearful for sharks. These apex predators play a key role in maintaining healthy reef ecosystems, but reef sharks rarely see fishing restrictions. This over fishing combined with coral bleaching due to warming seas, are creating a severe decline in shark populations. To learn more about the challenges our seas face and the solutions, check out the work of my friends Paul and Cristina at @sea_legacy #sharks #climatechange #underwater #tuamotus #fisheries #nature

Endangered Landscapes: For those in the Bay Area, I‚Äôm excited to share stories at Stanford University April 21 about my 800-mile photographic odyssey through the Grand Canyon,  Colorado River landscapes and the challenges they all face. More info in bio link.
For many Navajo, Hopi,  canyon lovers and others, this image is a sacred landscape, a natural church, believed to be best left for nature. For others, it is the best place for a 1.4-mile-long tramway into the heart of the Grand Canyon, carrying up to 10,000 people a day.  The economics and philosophy of this proposal, have divided the Navajo nation around it which is planning a vote on the project ‚Äúsoon‚Äù. Native Navajo Jason Nez, standing in the image, is fighting to keep the landscape undeveloped, but he is also acutely aware of the economic drought his nation faces. He wants to find economic alternatives. #chasingrivers #grandcanyon #nature #navajo #confluence üì∑#petemcbride thx for support  @hyperlite_mountain_gear @goalzero @4cornerfilmlogistics @delormegps

Amazon by foot: Once upon a time, my friend @ed_stafford spent over a year walking the length of the Amazon River ‚Äî a mind boggling 4345-mile journey. Why? Well, because it the world‚Äôs longest river and such a journey by foot had never been done. How he did it is another question. All I know is I got to follow him for a couple weeks through inky, mysterious waters, nervous about what lurked below. Despite a close encounter with a 10-foot electric eel, little happened beyond a few hundred bug bites, lots of thorns and some blisters. #MattPower, the talented writer that joined me (left of image), tragically passed away on another story walking another river, the Nile. I miss his joyous laughter and remarkable fearlessness daily. #amazonriver #archive #chasingrivers #nature #adventure üì∑@pedromcbride

Reflections on the world of water. In all my travels, water is life -- and lately a concern. In Northern Kenya, water comes from the glacier outflow of 17,000 ft. Mt. Kenya. But today, a changing climate has dwindled 16 glaciers to just over one ‚Äî changing the patterns or runoff to either flood or drought which has stressed the lives of many including the Samburu Tribe, pastoralists that depend on tracking scarce water supplies. I‚Äôm honored  to give the keynote talk for @nature_org at the botanical gardens in Dallas Texas sharing my decade of work around freshwater. Thx @sararacamp & @grownandsewn for duds. #kenya #samburu #freshwater #sarara #nature #climatechange üì∑#petemcbride

Window to water: On our 800-mile journey though the Grand Canyon,  the hunt for water drove everything from our movements to even our moods. The Danish island of Bornholm has four of these round churches. This one, the √òsterlars Church, was built around 1160.  Still in use. @natgeo @natgeocreative #lindbladexpeditions #denmark  @natgeoexpeditions

The pretty harbor on Christians√∏, Denmark. On a calm morning with the island to ourselves. The Brits once bombarded the island but were afraid of the guns in the tower-- but there weren't any! @natgeo @natgeocreative @natgeoexpeditions #lindbladexpeditions #denmark #island

Marching through the glens of Strathdon, the Lonach Highland and Friendly Society gathering is a classic scene from the summer Highland game season of Scotland. It was formed in 1823, mostly to preserve Highland dress and the Gaelic language (among others,) it harks back to an even earlier era when one of the main products of the Highlands was soldiers for the Scottish Regiments. It‚Äôs always the fourth Saturday of August and, to me, one of the finest of the games to be seen. There‚Äôs much more in our story on the Scottish Moors in the may issue of National Geographic. @natgeo @natgeocreative #scotland #lonach #lonachgames

The layered bens and glens of the Scottish Moors make the Cairngorms National Park a highlight for anyone seeking to understand this rich landscape. Our story in the May issue of National Geographic explores both the scenic wonders and the making of these lands, which owe as much to man-made influences as to nature. Even here you can see the stripes in the heather indicating that gamekeepers have been doing their jobs, burning the heather so that rich regrowth can nurture the red grouse. And tucked into the valleys are tree farms, a controversial land use in Scotland. But the hills themselves are magnificent and I was luck to see it that morning. #Scotland @natgeocreative #nature @natgeo

D√∫n Aonghasa (anglicized Dun Aengus) on Inishmore in the Aran Islands of Ireland.  The famous hill fort is protected by concentric walled defenses on one side and 300 foot sheer cliffs on the other.  Seeing it from a helicopter I got a view of both. It‚Äôs very old, of course, some of it going back to 1100 BC, maybe. But it never had a water supply so you can‚Äôt see how defenders would withstand a siege for long. I appreciate that they still haven‚Äôt built a fence along the cliff edge. It‚Äôs extremely scary but also thrilling. Nobody falls off. @natgeo @natgeocreative #ireland

The Aran Islands (Irish: Oile√°in √Årann) are indeed crisscrossed with many stone walls, some of which are very ancient. But there was also a proliferation of building in the last several centuries as families grew and fields were sub-divided and then divided again. The construction is drystane, meaning that there is no mortar used, so a great deal of skill is involved if they are to last. They are also constructed so the wind can pass through some, otherwise the fierce Atlantic gales would tear them down. It‚Äôs an inspiring place for a nonconformist like me. @natgeo @natgeocreative #ireland

Looking down on Irishman (Inis Me√°in) in the Aran Islands (Irish: Oile√°in √Årann) you can connect the Iron Age with the modern world and see many of the steps in between.  D√∫n Chonch√∫ir (Conor's Fort) is a ringfort started in pre-Christian times that is now surrounded by a maze of stone walls dividing fields and pastures. You can see how the road veered around as life developed in one continuous process from then till now.  And it‚Äôs quite possible that local folk living there now carry the genes of their ancestors who built the place. @natgeo @natgeocreative #ireland #history

In doing this shoot with @talulah_lamaison I had to tell them, I have no idea what femininity means! I find femininity vs masculinity confusing in many ways as there have been such huge changes to their definitions throughout our past. Recently I appreciate when others recognize the part of me that wants to sometimes wear dresses or heels or make up, although all of these have historically been equally worn by men. Too often society expects us to choose feminine or masculine and once it seems we've chosen, we're then expected to stick with that choice. I choose both. #BeYouBeTrue

How do I stay motivated? The truth is that I just do what I love. There is no better feeling than having a healthy and strong body that can carry you through life. I'm not extreme with a certain diet or with my training. I enjoy healthy food because I know my body needs it but I also make exceptions if I have cravings for something, without feeling quilty. I do the type of training I feel like doing, I'm challenging myself and I set new goals but I also take a few days of rest or choose to just go for a walk if I feel like it. Don't be so hard on yourself or on your body. Balance is the key üíó

I never expected my Instagram to get as big as it is today and it's really amazing but also a bit scary for me. Believe it or not but I'm really shy and I've never preferred to be in the center of attention. What I do love is to create and to inspire and motivate other people, that's what I'm able to do through my Instagram. 
Today I decided to step out of my comfort zone and did a live stream on my second account @nystrom.photo , since it's a bit smaller. I really want to share more with you and get to know you better but at the same time I slowly need to overcome my fear of talking in front of people, even if it's just through a screen. I'm so thankful to have so many kind and supportive people here from all over the world üôèüèª‚ò∫Ô∏èüíó

‚Üü in 1913 the Austrian Monarchy decided to build a pneumological clinic near Brixen, then already a well-known cultural centre. It's hard to sum up what critical temperatures are in a short sentence, but essentially it's when an animal starts to feel cold. I've read that for bison it's around -50 Fahrenheit.  Thick fur and a healthy layer of fat built up from grazing all summer help insulate the American bison from sub zero temps. "Waking up for sunrise is sooooooo worth it here!!!! After a starry night, this was our wake up view at The Wedge..... And as if it wasn't perfect enough before; when taking this shot suddenly the seagulls flew just right in front of the sun..... Moving up north from Perth along the coastline has given us already so many spectacular photo-moments, and we are only a couple of hundred km away from Perth.... I was thinking today that I am already 3 months in Australia! It has been an amazing journey so far, a journey through beautiful landscapes, but also a journey within! I am very grateful for all the moments I've had so far, the good and the 'bad', as it feels it definitely opened my eyes and gave me a different view on life! May I thank you all who followed us on our journey so far! My daily posts became also a bit of a blog; a way of emptying my mind and sharing my thoughts and Insights and I am very thankful that you take some time to read it and give some feedback every now and then! Of course life doesn't depend on the amount of likes or comments, but it's nice every now and then to get some feedback from others and feeling 'connected' even when being so far away! üòò"

My big sister Laura holds my father Wayne Guttenfelder's portrait as we drive to the cemetery this morning during his funeral in Waukee, Iowa.

My Father's Shoes

When I was growing up, Wayne Guttenfelder always wore black wingtip shoes. He wore them when he went to the office. He wore them while visiting my school principal when I was in trouble again. He even wore them in the barn to feed livestock on our family farm in Iowa. He wore holes in the soles and heels of every pair he owned.

Tomorrow morning I'm going to wear these wingtips to his funeral. My dad passed away on April 10th at age 75. My dad fought like a hero for 12 years after suffering a devastating stroke and battling lymphoma. 
I've been bragging about my dad for my whole life. When I was a boy, he was a Golden Gloves boxer and he covered the walls of our house with his paintings of cartoon characters. He was big hearted, a fearless risk taker and a wily practical joker. I am very proud of who he was and very proud of the ways I've lived to be like him. 
For those who knew him, a celebration of his life will be held on Saturday, April 22 at 10:30am at the Waukee, Iowa United Methodist Church.

Did you know that cats are obligate carnivores? That they must, by their nature, live on a diet of meat? They do not or no longer have the ability to digest vegetable matter. Cats living in the wild chase and kill small prey such as rodents, mice, squirrels, rabbits, reptiles, amphibians, birds, insects, and sometimes small fish. Feeding a raw meat diet is our way of getting as close as is practical to a diet that cats evolved to eat. ~
All of our pets enjoy a raw diet from @bigcountryraw. Head on over to their feed and their website (link in their bio) to learn more about how raw could be a healthy choice for your pet.

Confluence, Canyonlands Utah. 
I've photographed the confluence of the Green and Colorado Rivers in Canyonlands National Park a lot in my career. Funny thing is that the best image I've ever made of it was with a smartphone. When I made this smartphone picture I realized that much in photography had changed. Good pictures were no longer going to be the exclusive domain of high-end cameras and professional photographers. Smartphones had come of age. They democratized photography! A photographer still has to know where and when to point the camera but the camera itself was no longer a huge factor. In the intervening years telephone cameras have only gotten better.

I'd like to know what people think about the smartphone's influence on photography. Opinions??? #utah #canyonlands #smartphone

One of thousands of sandstone shelters that dot Southern Utah. I don‚Äôt know the percentage but many of these show signs of human occupation dating from the first arrival of people to the South West.

#utah #cave #bearsears @thephotosociety

@thatssorach takes in the view from an enormous cave in Comb Ridge. Shelters like this provided shelter for the first inhabitants of the South West. This cave is still littered with obvious evidence of human habitation hundreds of years after people have moved on to other abode. #utah #bearsears
Long straight red road east of Hanksville Utah.

4 negative and one positive handprint in a cave in San Juan County Utah. Handprints have to be the most ubiquitous form of rock art. I've seen them the world over. They are the original signature. The first sign that "I was here."
#rockart #Utah

Evening petroglyph shoot in Comb Wash.
The new Bears Ears National Monument is a cultural treasure. The land in the monument is central to the histories of the  native people of the Southwest. Signs of their time here is everywhere. #ancientartarchive #keepitpublic #bearsears #utah

The top of Comb Ridge in the new Bears Ears National Monument. 
The quiet here is so profound. Except for the occasional buzz of a fly or the trill of a canyon wren it's as if there is an absence of sound. The only other place I've experienced that is northern Namibia. The Bears Ears is stunning and belongs to us all. #keepitpublic #bearsears #utah

The first time I saw Barrier Canyon Style rock art was in Sego Canyon. The figures intimidated me so much at the time! I still find them spooky but more enigmatic that frightening. Rock art is a window into the world view of its creator. The subject still fascinates me! #utah

Angry people are like zits. They glare you and try to get you pop them, but if you do you'll just make them worse. No really, I mean it. As someone that has had acne my entire life, I really see the analogy. And it's no coincidence that when my hormones are raging I break break out (you know that once a month zit you can't avoid). But maybe it's also about timing? You know there's a time to broach a subject, a time to pop a zit, and if you get it wrong, well you can leave little scars either on your face or in your heart. I've got a bunch of scars all over the place, mostly in the heart. With a good dermatologist and a few facial peels the acne scars go away, but the ones left in the heart, those stay around for awhile. So my best advice, when someone's angry don't engage with them. Wait for them to cool down. If you're angry, don't engage with others, don't run headfirst into a battle where no one will ever win. Calm down first. Wait. Breathe. Return to center. I hate looking in the mirror and seeing the mountain a zit. It's like they sprout and grow overnight from some twisted place in the universe that's sole purpose is to annoy you. And I want them gone right away. But I've learned to look in the mirror and just let them be there (with a little cover up just to appease my vanity and bc if I don't see them I'm less likely to touch them and poke at them). And the same thing with anger, it's so hard to look yourself in the eye when you're harboring any kind of negativity. It's even harder to look someone in the eye who's mad at you. But it all comes back to this. A quiet moment, the veneer pulled back to reveal the truth, that underneath all anger is a tiny wound, an infection, a little broken heart that needs time and space to heal, that itself wants to be free of what's clogging it, and eventually will get itself sorted out. In the meanwhile no need to try and fix it, just breathe and be strong enough to watch it all with a kind and open heart (and apply a good, non-irritating spot treatment, sometimes also known as a hug). üôè
.

What's in a handstand? Nothing if not the journey. My mind is naturally jumpy, which means I fluctuate from depression to anxiety, from euphoric mania to self-pity with a rapidity that is both daunting and honestly a bit exhausting. I have an awful tendency to take things personally and I'm overly sensitive to criticism. Add to that I'm ambitious, competitive and harsh on myself. I came to yoga with all that baggage and then some. My journey to handstand has been about slowly, steadily walking the middle way between emotional extremes. Anyone can do it, both the handstand and the calm mind. But it's a training and it requires your consistent, persistent practice. The last 48 hours have been emotionally challenging. I don't know why but a lot of my old triggers came up. I've been annoyed at the world, hard on myself for even reacting, feeling self-pity (why does this always happen to me?), and just generally filled with an empty loneliness. Without the grounding of my practice I'd be lost. The practice isn't God, but it's a way that I can drop down under the surface of all my stuff and feel His presence. Today my practice consisted of 20 minutes of meditation and prayer, 10 minutes of strength drills, 80 minutes of Ashtanga Yoga. Somewhere in the midst of all that the quality of my thoughts changed, I started to relax, appreciate life, tune into joy and positive expectation and I became quiet and still. And in that stillness I was restored by Grace, my Mercy, by the ultimate act of Forgiveness and Surrender. And now I just sit with two words: thank you, the best mantra ever, thank you. üôè
.

Sometimes I dream about yoga. Do you? Whenever I dream about the poses they always show up with much more ease and it's always a pose that I'm blocked at in real life. Like when I was learning handstands I would dream about them all the time. Handstand press, one arm transitions (still can't do), tic-tocs, everything! I'd be flying on my arms at night. Then I'd wake up excited to practice. A small childish part of me thought maybe the dream would be magically real that day in practice but it often took years of hard work to get close to what I'd dreamt. Sometimes I dream about things I want so badly but I have no control over. Lately I dream about my Dad. I see him standing, walking, talking, driving, eating a falafel (he ate his first falafel at my wedding), playing cards (he loves blackjack), holding my hand, just healthy, better, recovered. And I wake up confused about which reality is real, and for a few moments I latch onto the dream as though it's real, but then I remember I'm here, in this world with its truths and its suffering, in this place in my life right now where it takes everything in me to believe in the impossible becoming possible. I believe in love, and maybe that's the real miracle, the only one we really truly need. üíó
.

I started practicing yoga when I was miserable having fun, I pushed partying too far and wound up angry on the dance floor. Truthfully I was running and distracting myself with "fun". Only when I finally got real enough to dig deeply into my own stuff was I able to find the seed of happiness. But... what is happiness? How much of what we call happiness is really just fun and entertainment? First I think it's useful to distinguish between the two. Happiness is the state of contentment, joy, satisfaction, rapture, well-being. Fun is amusement, pleasure, diversion, entertainment. Can someone have fun and be unhappy? Oh yes. Can someone be deeply happy but not so entertaining? Oh yes. The question perhaps is what to value and prioritize. If you focus simply on what is immediately entertaining and pleasurable you might miss out on what will actually make you happy and fulfilled. Now, it's not to say they can't be one and the same. But lately I am finding people who practice yoga in search of fun and the moment it gets difficult, the fun is gone and they want to quit. But happiness isn't always about fast and easy, sometimes it's about slow and meaningful. I think yoga has so much potential because it helps us confront our own limitations. We see that may be addicted to fun to the detriment of depth and presence. Or we may see that we are too serious and need a little bit of humor. Whatever your practice is, wherever you are in your journey, yoga helps you see clearly. And in that clarity your whole world changes. üôè
.

Yoga isn't easy. To try and make it easy is like trying to make brain surgery easy. But yoga can be done with ease and flow. You can stress out over anything and everything. Or you can learn to do things with ease and flow. If all you ever do is stay in what's already easy for you then how will you grow as a person? Your yoga practice is an operation of the mind and an education in the spirit. The poses and practices that challenge you the most are where you learn the most. Once you can remain calm and equanimous in a difficult pose the idea is that you're more likely to maintain that state of inner peace in difficult life situations.  This is the essence of the practice for me. Start to measure your success not in how powerful your lift up is, but in how much kindness and tranquility you bring to the world. üíó
.

If you can take the ordinary moments in life and make them extraordinary just by brining your attention to them, then every day is magical and every being matters. In every situation you can choose to be miserable or you can focus on what good there is. Turn your face to the sun, not the shadow. You have a choice about how you think and what you think. Your thoughts have power, maybe more than you realize. Don't make up a fantasy world where you're living a fake dream of false happiness. Stick to the reality and look for the goodness, the light. It's there in every situation and in every person. It's there, the light, the smile, the love. You matter, your choices matter, not only to yourself but to the world. The day you start really choosing your own happiness is the day that your life changes. You're worth it, your worth thinking good thoughts about. This world can be a blessing or a curse. What's crazy is that it's your choice which to make it. And honestly that's kind of scary because it means we are each responsible for our own happiness and not victims to a big bad world that's out to get us or keep us down. For today watch your thoughts as you practice and go through life. Notice how many complaints appear as opposed to statements of gratitude. Start off by just observing and then slowly replace one objection with one little appreciation. üôè

I used to rush around and worry about everything. I'm not sure when it shifted but it definitely did. A travel day like yesterday would have made me nuts, but I was calm and didn't rush once. When I was about to take off in Miami I got a notice saying my flight to Sydney was delayed by four hours. When I landed in LA I found out that the flight had been diverted to Honolulu and while Hawaii is awesome I needed to get to Australia. Checking the flight board I saw another flight with Qantas, got rebooked and had my luggage transferred (verdict is still out on whether or not that worked, I'll find out at the luggage belt in Sydney). Then, all boarded and ready to take off on the new flight only to sit on the runway because of unmatchable passenger numbers. It took nearly two hours to get the tallies and names right on the flight roster.  How I was neither freaking out nor totally impatient is a miracle, the quality of my thoughts were peaceful and quiet, forgiving and grateful. I mean, I usually have at least few deep sighs of irritation and I'm honestly shocked that I didn't. I guess this yoga thing works. Look for the evidence of your practice reflected back to you in the images of your and in the vibration of your thoughts. I slept for 11 of the 15 hours on the flight. Now I'm landing and it looks like a beautiful sunny day. ‚òÄÔ∏è
.

I'm not a numbers person, I don't read my bank statements as carefully as I should. We did our accounts this morning and got struck with the voice of fear. It whispered to us in doubt and tried to make us think that that our dreams aren't going to work out, that we will never make it, that's there's not ever going to be enough. It was loud and stressful and my shoulder even started to hurt. But we decided not to listen. I like to operated from the belief that everything is going to be ok, that there is more than enough. But belief is a choice, like changing the dial of your radio station, except it works by choosing which thoughts you're going to listen to. So we tuned in to the voice of faith, a quiet presence of wisdom that sustains you though feast and famine. Faith says, I will always provide for you, even when you're at your limit and on your last penny, I will not let you down. Stay strong, what is meant to be will be, what is not meant to be cannot be forced. There is only one power in the universe that can create something out of nothing. With faith, manna can rain down blessings from heaven in your life. Without faith, you're lost in the desert of doubt on your own. You don't need to know the grand plan, nor do you need to know exactly how it's all going to work out. You certainly don't need to sweat the small stuff. You just need unshakable faith and the power of your conviction will carry you forward. So... when faced with a mountain of doubt, when adversity strikes, when scarcity shows up, the question is... Do you believe? Are you strong enough to keep the faith? Live in faith or live in fear. It's your choice. üôè
.
